(In Chambers) Order by Judge Stanley Blumenfeld, Jr.: Plaintiff's motion to remand contains significant, concerning errors. For instance, it cites to a nonexistent case and quotes language that does not appear in the complaint. By September 25, 2024, Plaintiff shall disclose, in writing, whether generative artificial intelligence was used to generate any portion of the filing, as required by the Civil Standing Order, and be prepared to address this issue at the mandatory scheduling conference.THERE IS NO PDF DOCUMENT ASSOCIATED WITH THIS ENTRY. (bk) TEXT ONLY ENTRY (Entered: 09/20/2024)

ORDER: IT IS ORDERED as follows: If any portion of a pleading or other document filed on this Court's docket has been drafted (in whole or in part) using generative artificial intelligence, including, but not limited to ChatGPT, Harvey.AI, or Google Bard, all attorneys and pro se litigants filingsuch pleadings or other documents shall verify that any language that was generated in any form by AI was checked for accuracy by using print reporters, traditional legal databases, or other reliable means by a human being. Signed by Judge James A Soto on 9/1/2023. (See attached Order for complete information.)(SCA) (Entered: 09/05/2023)

MINUTE entry before the Honorable Gabriel A. Fuentes: Upon the parties' report that they did not ultimately reach an agreement to settle the matter, SAP counsel Alan Rhine is discharged and thanked for his service. Plaintiff is now pro se in the litigation. The parties are directed to review and comply with the Court's Standing Order for Civil Cases Before Magistrate Judge Fuentes, available on the Court's website and revised as of 5/31/23, with the most recent revisions concerning the use of generative artificial intelligence in the preparation of documents filed with the magistrate judge under any applicable referral, or all filed documents if the matter is before the magistrate judge on consent. Mailed notice. (lxk, ) (Entered: 05/31/2023)
